Steps to Follow

Set Up Your Project

Create a new folder, e.g., css-exercises.

Inside, create:

index.html

style.css

Link your CSS file in your HTML:

<link rel="stylesheet" href="style.css">


Exercise Categories
These are common CSS exercises TOP suggests:

1. Selectors and Styling

Target elements by:

Type (p, h1)

Class (.classname)

ID (#idname)

Tasks:

Change colors

Add fonts

Set background images

2. Box Model

Practice with:

width, height

padding, margin

border

div {
  width: 200px;
  height: 100px;
  padding: 10px;
  margin: 20px;
  border: 2px solid black;
}

3. Positioning

Explore:

static, relative, absolute, fixed, sticky

.box {
  position: relative;
  top: 20px;
  left: 50px;
}

4. Flexbox

Layout exercises:

.container {
  display: flex;
  justify-content: space-between;
  align-items: center;
}

5. Grid

Create grid layouts:

.grid-container {
  display: grid;
  grid-template-columns: 1fr 2fr 1fr;
  gap: 10px;
}

6. Responsive Design

Use media queries:

@media (max-width: 600px) {
  body {
    background-color: lightblue;
  }
}

7. Pseudo-classes & Pseudo-elements

Examples:

a:hover {
  color: red;
}

p::first-letter {
  font-size: 2rem;
}

8. Transitions & Animations

Add smooth effects:

div {
  transition: all 0.3s ease;
}

div:hover {
  transform: scale(1.1);
}

Git Practice

Initialize a repo:

git init
git add .
git commit -m "Initial commit for CSS exercises"
git branch -M main
git remote add origin <your-repo-url>
git push -u origin main


Commit after completing each exercise to track progress.

Tips

Don’t hesitate to copy snippets from MDN to learn how things work.

Inspect elements in the browser to see live changes.

Focus on understanding why a style works, not just how to write it.
